<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-134-938  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 134 938.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Banking  March 1989 v6 n3 p22(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taking uncommon - but effective - steps for computer security.andO;(systems management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Samid, Gideon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer security is threatened by the nature of a computer's ownconfiguration, especially stationary networks.andP;  Hackers have theadvantage of surprise and a global entry capability.andP;  Severalsecurity measures are available to deter unauthorized entry intodata files, although no computer is completely safe fromintrusion.andP;  'Drowning' is a method that hides importantinformation within data that is actually garbage and not useful.andO;Cost-benefit factors come into play when it takes more time tosort through files than the sought after information is worth tobegin with.andP;  'Traps' are programs that engage intruders in adialogue while the system is being invaded.andP;  Meanwhile the hackeris being tracked down by the computer's security system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Access ControlsData IntegritySecuritySecurity SoftwareMISManagement of EDPCommunications TappingComputer CrimesPlanning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>